@realmoney Sep 28, 2020 | 09:37 AM EDT DOUG KASS Trade of the Week (and Fourth Quarter): Long Amazon If equities hold up over the near term and over the next 100 days, Amazon's ($AMZN) shares stand to be a strong beneficiary. The company's moat has deepened since the spread of

Covid-19 and there are no other companies (save Walmart ($WMT) , which I am also long) that have the financial resources and operating expertise to compete against this online behemoth. Amazon's first adopter advantage has morphed into a likely permanent position of leadership

in the broad array of end markets it serves. Remember when Apple ($AAPL) was a "must own" stock and dominated financial TV, the Indices and exchange-traded funds? Given the above, I expect Amazon to assume that mantle in the days, weeks and months ahead. Here is my investment
case of nearly two years ago, which suggests a $5,000 price target. Amazon was placed on my Best Ideas List at $1,383 on Dec. 26, 2018. The shares closed on Friday at $3,095.

Coming up on @realmoney One Man Gathers What Another Man Spills * Step out of your comfort range * Why I am short term bullish piped.video/watch?v=g6mS-drQ… I have often written that opinions are like assholes - everyone has one. Vitriolic, partisan discourse in politics has been a

low note these days. And, too often we debate markets with the same source of dogma and lack of objectivity that exists in our political debates. I can almost tell how someone will interpret the markets (Bull or Bear or something in between) by the person that voices their

views. In general, views have become predictable despite the existence of so much uncertainty and possible outcomes (many of them adverse). I find this predetermination odd. (It takes many market forms - from Perma Bull to Perma Bear, from gold bugs to those that recoil at the

suggestion of purchasing precious metals. In politics it is Liberal v. Conservative, Democrat v. Republican). And something to avoid. Many find my market view today somewhat perplexing - as for days I have been bullish short term and bearish intermediate term.

But I endeavor to remain objective and I am committed to looking at all considerations and factors (even charts) when I analyze what is increasingly an ever more complex investment mosaic. I certainly have no concession of the investment truth. I start the day large net long.
